03979nam a22006255i 9780292784796DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927847967 a10.7560/7227502doi  a(DE-B1597)588541  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aGN585.G85 ǂb P37 2010eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a9381 aPatterson, Lee E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKinship Myth in Ancient Greece /cLee E. Patterson. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (271 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tNote on Translations and Transliterations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- t1. Kinship and Constructed Identities -- t2. Credulity and Historical Causation -- t3. Kinship Myth in the Literary Sources -- t4. Kinship Myth in the Literary Sources -- t5. Alexander the Great -- t6. Epigraphical Evidence of Kinship Diplomacy -- t7. Epigraphical Evidence of Kinship Diplomacy -- t8. Conclusions -- tAppendix One. The Historical Context of Plutarch, solon 8–10 -- tAppendix Two. Greek Myth and Macedonian Identity -- tAppendix Three. A Tale of Two Phoci -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tGeneral Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn ancient Greece, interstate relations, such as in the formation of alliances, calls for assistance, exchanges of citizenship, and territorial conquest, were often grounded in mythical kinship. In these cases, the common ancestor was most often a legendary figure from whom both communities claimed descent. In this detailed study, Lee E. Patterson elevates the current state of research on kinship myth to a consideration of the role it plays in the construction of political and cultural identity. He draws examples both from the literary and epigraphical records and shows the fundamental difference between the two. He also expands his study into the question of Greek credulity—how much of these founding myths did they actually believe, and how much was just a useful fiction for diplomatic relations? Of central importance is the authority the Greeks gave to myth, whether to elaborate narratives or to a simple acknowledgment of an ancestor. Most Greeks could readily accept ties of interstate kinship even when local origin narratives could not be reconciled smoothly or when myths used to explain the link between communities were only "discovered" upon the actual occasion of diplomacy, because such claims had been given authority in the collective memory of the Greeks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCivilization, Ancient. 0aKinshipzGreecexHistory. 0aMythology, Greek. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292784796423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292784796/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK